node.text:
Today we announce the 35 photographers selected for the upcoming #PhotoVogueFestival exhibition through the open call on #PhotoVogue, @Picter_com and Instagram. On Picter alone we received 24.913 images, 2.949 projects by 2.513 photographers from 98 different countries, 6 continents. 
 
Here are the selected artists: @tendercoconut_, @Alessandro.Iovino_, @BettinaPittaluga, @BryanThomasphoto, @delaliayivi, @diiegotv, @di_mathopa, @ElenaHelfrecht, @Elliott.Verdier, @FabioLasin, @Gabriele.Cecconi, @heathatrottlives, @Reanie_Beanie, @l4artiste, @jaircoll, @JodiemBateman, @Juan_Brenner, @Kaiykym, @LauraPannack, @lebo.th, @LeonardPongo, @LisandroSuriel, @Kuca_Magda, @MousLamrabat, @plantationofficial, @elriveriver, @RobertAndyCoombs2, @tondopo, @SaraBennettBrooklyn, @SilvanaTrevale, @SuleikaMueller, @Sushavan_Nandy, @africatotheworldzw, @thembinkosih15, @panremembrance. The artists have been selected by an international jury consisting of experts from across the world, with different backgrounds and vision so as to try to provide the most inclusive and multifaceted perspective. 
 
Photo Vogue Festival has always tried to challenge the danger of single, monolithic stories, and to push a multiplicity of points of view. For its 6th edition, titled “Reframing History”, we wanted to explore the projects that have reclaimed an alternative, different way of telling a tale. 
For the very first time - as part of the Reframing History scouting initiative - PVF launched a grant in collaboration with Studio RM, a prestigious creative studio with offices in London and New York, specialising in colour grading and post production for film, print and digital.
The two participants that will receive a 5,000€ cash grant each, are Lisandro Suriel and River Claure. 
 
Discover more about #VIReframingHistory at the link in bio.

Insieme a @WWFItalia siamo andati alla scoperta dell'Oasi WWF Le Cesine. L'Oasi si trova all'interno di un Sito d'Importanza Comunitaria nel Comune di Vernole e il suo simbolo è la beccaccia di mare.
 
La storia di questa straordinaria Oasi, in provincia di Lecce, comincia il 13 ottobre del 1939, quando viene affittata alla sezione cacciatori di Lecce. Nel 1964 per Decreto Ministeriale viene istituita la “Riserva di caccia Cesine” e negli anni successivi le mattanze ai danni della fauna si susseguono senza sosta.
 
Ma la firma della Convenzione di Ramsar nel 1971 cambia le sorti dell’area e il 1/1/1976 Le Cesine diventano un’area di tutela e rifugio per animali selvatici. Nel 1977, a seguito della ratifica della Convenzione di Ramsar avvenuta l’anno prima, l’area diviene Zona Umida di Interesse Internazionale.
 
Il paesaggio de Le Cesine è costituito da dune, area palustre, canali di bonifica, bosco misto e macchia mediterranea. Oggi l'Oasi protegge 350 ettari ed è un ambiente umido tra i meglio conservati e più importanti dell'Italia meridionale, e si trova lungo una delle principali rotte migratorie per l’avifauna e vi sono state censite circa 180 specie di uccelli. Notevolissime sono anche le presenze di anfibi, rettili e insetti.
 
A guidarci in questo viaggio Giuseppe De Matteis, Responsabile RNS Oasi Le Cesine.
 #WWFItalia

node.text:
The fashion industry has long-been synonymous with over-working - measured in its weight by the backbone of hyperproductivity, and the relentless quest to meet the demands of its ever-expanding calendar. With headlines like: ‘Is Fashion Speeding Towards Burnout?’ (WWD), and ‘Fashion World Fears Designer Burnout As Pressure Takes Its Toll’ (The Guardian), previously serving as a dystopian reflection of the expectations placed upon anyone choosing to land a place within the coveted industry. But along with everything else that Covid-19 has forced us to confront – our unhealthy attitude towards work has been at the forefront. Even at the upper levels of the industry, high profile figures have been shining a light on the importance of putting their wellbeing first. So, for an industry marked by its normalization of burn-out, what does the future look like post-Covid?

In the #VogueItalia’s September Issue, @SamiraLarouci goes deeper into the topic. Read more via link in bio. 
Photographed by @NicoKrijno.
